{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659578"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:11:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20871"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20871"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13746"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96518"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13746","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13746"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79160"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11595"},{"type":"tags","id":"12325"},{"type":"tags","id":"12694"},{"type":"tags","id":"12696"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33082"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96518"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to a sexual health clinic for HIV testing after a recent unprotected sexual encounter. He is concerned about the natural progression of HIV infection should his test be positive.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the early events in HIV infection?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initial viral replication limited to the bloodstream","Viral capture by dendritic cells with lymph node dissemination","Rapid development of opportunistic infections","Immediate destruction of CD8+ T cells","Prolonged asymptomatic period before viral replication"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Eviral capture by dendritic cells with lymph node dissemination\u003C/strong\u003E. After mucosal infection, dendritic cells (DCs) in the epithelium at the site of virus entry capture HIV particles. These DCs then migrate to lymph nodes where they transfer the virus to CD4+ T cells through direct cell-to-cell contact. Within days of initial exposure, viral replication begins in the lymph nodes, leading to viremia with high numbers of viral particles in the bloodstream. The virus then disseminates throughout the body, infecting helper T cells, macrophages, and dendritic cells in peripheral lymphoid tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate destruction of CD8+ T cells\u003C/strong\u003E - HIV primarily targets CD4+ T cells, not CD8+ T cells. While CD8+ T cell function may be impaired during HIV infection, their immediate destruction is not a characteristic early event.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitial viral replication limited to the bloodstream\u003C/strong\u003E - Viral replication begins in lymphoid tissues, particularly lymph nodes, before significant viremia occurs. The bloodstream serves as a route of dissemination rather than the primary site of initial replication.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERapid development of opportunistic infections\u003C/strong\u003E - Opportunistic infections typically occur in later stages of HIV infection when CD4+ T cell counts have significantly declined. They are not characteristic of early infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged asymptomatic period before viral replication\u003C/strong\u003E - Viral replication begins within days of infection, not after a prolonged asymptomatic period. While there is often an asymptomatic clinical latency period after acute infection, viral replication is ongoing during this time.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["HIV infection begins with mucosal infection followed by viral dissemination and host immune response development.","Dendritic cells capture HIV at epithelial entry sites and transport it to lymph nodes where they transfer the virus to CD4+ T cells.","Viral replication in lymph nodes occurs within days of exposure, leading to viremia with high viral loads in the bloodstream.","During dissemination, HIV infects helper T cells, macrophages, and dendritic cells throughout peripheral lymphoid tissues."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 6; page 253."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79160"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20871"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79160","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79160"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T18:41:57+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T18:43:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13746"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96518"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11595"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diseases of the immune system","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":5,